            <p>From the chronicles of the early years of Spanish colonization, reports about Masbate first appeared in July 1569 when Fray Martin de Rada wrote to the Viceroy of New Spain (Mexico), Marquis de Falces. He mentioned that in a place called Masbat there were plenty of gold and mines. Other later documents such as those of Artieda’s Ralacion (1573) and Andres de Mirandaola’s letter (1574) reported of a place called Masbat or Masbad.</p>
            <p>The name variation is understandable as Spaniards spoke in an aspirated manner. Masbad must have been pronounced Masbat by the Spanish tongue. In 1582, Miguel de Lorca reported about a place called Masbate. This was the first time the name was used in place of Masbad or Masbat.</p>
            <p>On September 30, 2000, Republic Act 8807 officially proclaimed the conversion of the Municipality of Masbate into a component city.</p>
            <p>Masbate is the capital of the Masbate province. The city’s total land area is 187.892811 square kilometers. It has 30 barangays, 11 of which are urban located in the Poblacion.</p>
            <p>Masbate is fulfilling its vision to become the country’s Marine Sanctuary by 2020.</p>

